## §5 — FAILURE-INJECTION LOCK-INS (P4)

The test injects a failure (DB error, network error, parse error) and asserts the system degrades **honestly** — surfaces the failure, doesn't silently corrupt state.

### Go: handler maps store error to correct status

```go
// Regression for: GET /tasks/{id} returned 500 when the task was actually missing,
// because the store error wasn't mapped to domain.ErrNotFound at the boundary.
func TestRegression_GetTask_returns_404_on_not_found(t *testing.T) {
    h, _ := newHandlerWithSQLite(t)
    req := httptest.NewRequest(http.MethodGet, "/tasks/does-not-exist", nil)
    rec := httptest.NewRecorder()
    h.ServeHTTP(rec, req)

    require.Equal(t, http.StatusNotFound, rec.Code)
    var body map[string]any
    require.NoError(t, json.Unmarshal(rec.Body.Bytes(), &body))
    require.NotEmpty(t, body["error"])
}
```

### Web: error UI on fetch failure

```ts
// Regression for: TasksPage rendered an empty list when /tasks returned 500,
// indistinguishable from "no tasks". Now must show error UI.
it("renders an error state when /tasks returns 500", async () => {
  server.use(http.get("/tasks", () => HttpResponse.json({ error: "boom" }, { status: 500 })));
